body:
It seems some constants cannot be used in match ranges, which is rather unfortunate if intended IMHO.

The following compiles without issues:

```
const TEST_CONST: i32 = 7;

fn main() {
    let n : i32 = 7;
    match n {
        TEST_CONST ... 17 => {},
        _ => {}
    }
}
```

If we make the constant global, it doesn't compile anymore,

```
static TEST_CONST: i32 = 7;

fn main() {
    let n : i32 = 7;
    match n {
        TEST_CONST ... 17 => {},
        _ => {}
    }
}
```

failing with the rather cryptic

```
not_working_static.rs:6:9: 6:19 error: non-constant path in constant expr
not_working_static.rs:6         TEST_CONST ... 17 => {},
                                ^~~~~~~~~~
```

If we use a constant defined in another crate, as in the following example,

```
use std::i32::MIN;

fn main() {
    let n : i32 = 7;
    match n {
        std::i32::MIN ... 17 => {},
        _ => {}
    }
}
```

 we get yet another error message

```
not_working_imported_constant.rs:6:23: 6:26 error: expected one of `::`, `=>`, `if`, or `|`, found `...`
not_working_imported_constant.rs:6         std::i32::MIN ... 17 => {},
                                                         ^~~
```

I don't know if it is intended, but if it is the error messages can likely be improved quite a bit.

```
$ rustc --version --verbose
